<h1> CALLIGRAPUFF </h1>
<p> Introduction: </p>
<p> <bold> Calligraphy is a visual art related to writing. It is the design and execution of lettering with a broad-tipped instrument, brush, or other writing instrument. A contemporary calligraphic practice can be defined as "the art of giving form to signs in an expressive, harmonious, and skillful manner" </bold> </p>
<h2> These are different type of brushes.</h2>
<img src="strokes.jpg" alt="Brush Tips" width="500" height="300">
<h2>⇝ Brushes, or markers with harder tips are easier to control,
 While brushes with softer tips are usually harder for beginners to use.</h2>
<h3>⇝ Crayola supertip markers are the easiest and cheapest markers to use for calligraphy.</h3>
<h3>⇝ That is why it is usually suggested to beginners.</h3>
<h3>⇝ Brush markers with soft tips are usually very fragile and more expensive </h3>
<img src="crayola.jpg" alt="crayola Tips" width="500" height="300">
<br>
<h2>⇝ This is an example of the alphabet and numbers in calligraphy.</h2>
<h2>⇝ It is expected for you guys to be able to write something similar to this after this session </h2>
<h2>⇝ There are also different fonts of calligraphy, but we’ll focus on the standard cursive </h2>
<img src="alphabet.jpg" alt="crayola Tips" width="550" height="350">
<h1>  This is the Basic Strokes </h1>
<h2>⇝ DOWNSTROKE: Heavy Pressure </h2>
<h2>⇝ OVERTURN: A combination of the up and down stroke. </h2>
<h2>⇝ UNDERTURN: Opposite of the overturn. </h2>
<h2>⇝ COMPOUND CURVE: A combination of the over and under turn.</h2>
<h2>⇝ OVAL: This is a tricky one and takes some practice! . </h2>
<h2>⇝ ASCENDING LOOP: This is a fun one!</h2>
<video width="770" height="400" controls>
  <source src="basicstrokes.mp4" type="video/mp4">
</video>
<h2>⇝ Practicing the basic strokes may seem like something that’s unnecessary, but it’s the key to learning calligraphy. </h2>
<h3>⇝ Practice the basic strokes on a daily basis in order to achieve the consistency you want</h3>
<h2> ⇝ A way to spice up your calligraphy is to add twirls and curls to the stems and tails of the letters.
</h2>
<h3>⇝ This is another reason for why you should practice the basic strokes. </h3>
<img src="strokes2.jpg" alt="strokes Tips" width="560" height="350">
<h1> Here are some of the different flows for how you can write your calligraphy; </h1>
<h2>⇝ The “exaggerated” where in the letters seem bouncy</h2>
<h3>⇝ The “balanced” where there is just a slight impartiality</h3>
<h2>⇝ The “subtle” where the letters are toned-down</h2>
<img src="ways.jpg" alt="different Tips" width="650" height="450">
